data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The Cosmos DB provider's **`AllowSynchronousIO()` escape hatch is removed**. In .NET 10 (EF Core 10) you could opt in to sync-over-async:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos("...", "...", cosmosOptions =>
    cosmosOptions.AllowSynchronousIO());  // ← gone in EF Core 11
```

In .NET 11, calling `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, or `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider throws **`InvalidOperationException`** unconditionally. There is no workaround — you **must** use async APIs.

## The fix

Convert every synchronous call to its async counterpart:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods become `async` and renamed with `Async` suffix
- `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`

All callers up the chain must also go async. This is intentional — sync-over-async on Cosmos was always a deadlock risk and perf hazard.
